Exploratory Sales Data Analysis & Visualization

Austin Oberg

3/25/2022

This analysis is a simple look at tech sales dataset from the year 2019, provided by Knightbearr on Kaggle.com at the following link: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/knightbearr/sales-product-data

The goal of this analysis is to provide answers to the following questions:

Q: What was the best month for sales? How much was earned that month?

Q: What city had the highest number of sales?

Q: What product sold the most? Why do you think it sold the most?

Q Which produt yielded the highest revenue?

To complete this project, I utilized Google Sheets, BigQuery, and R Programming Language.

Data aggregation and cleaning in SQL and Excel

The first step in processing this data was loading each month table into BigQuery and unioning them together. I exported this aggregated table from BigQuery into Google Sheets, where I used SPLIT and CONCATENATE to remove the timestamp from the column Date. I exported this as a .csv file and then repeated the process for the column Purchase Address to remove address number information. I uploaded both .csv files back into BigQuery to create new views for analysis and visualization. These views were saved as .csv files and loaded into R with read.csv(). From here I began answering questions.

Analysis

ggplot(units_sold_mo %>% 
         group_by(Date,Product) %>% 
         summarize_at("Quantity_Sold", sum, na.rm=T),
       aes(Date, Quantity_Sold, fill = Product)) + 
  geom_bar(stat="sum",na.rm=TRUE) +
  ggtitle("Total Sales by Month") +
  xlab("Month") + ylab("Units Sold") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45))

We start with a plot of Total Sales by Month. Looking at this gives us a clear answer to our first question. December had the highest number of sales in 2019. Using the following code chunk, I was able to ascertain that the amount of revenue from that month totaled was $4,569,702.

I there may be a corollary relationship between number of sales during and the time of year they occur. This relationship may be supported by the number of sales in December as compared to the rest of the year, due to the holidays. It may also be supported by April’s numbers, as there are Americans who receive tax refunds during April.

It looks like San Francisco has the highest number of sales at 50,169, with a total revenue of $8,170,654 which is 23.9% of the total amount earned in 2019.

I went straight to a ggplot to determine which product sold the most:

ggplot(product_totals, aes(x = factor(`Product`))) + 
  geom_bar(aes(weight = Quantity_Ordered, fill = `Product`, color = `Product`)) +
  ggtitle("Total Sales by Product") +
  xlab("Product") + ylab("Units Sold") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  annotate('text', x = '34in Ultrawide Monitor', y = 30000, label = 'Batteries', color = 'dark green', angle = 70) +
  annotate('text', x = 'ThinkPad Laptop', y = 24750, label = 'Apple Charging Cables', color = 'dark magenta', angle = 15)

Batteries! This makes perfect sense. People go through batteries pretty quickly, especially AAA batteries. However, the vast difference between the quantities sold of batteries and MacBooks may make the next plot surprising.

ggplot(revenue_totals, aes(x = factor(`Product`))) + 
  geom_bar(aes(weight = Total_Revenue, color = `Product`)) +
  ggtitle("Revenue vs. Product") +
  xlab("Product") + ylab("Revenue") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank()) +
  annotate('text', x = 'Lightning Charging Cable', y = 8200000, label = 'Macbook Prop Laptop,$8,030,800', color = 'purple') +

Unfortunately, I do not have data on product manufacturing cost or freight expenses. It would be interesting to look at which product turns the most profit, both proportionally, and as a total. The Macbook generated over $8 million in revenue in 2019, while selling about 5,000 units.

Summary & Conclusion

We can see from this data that most sales occur in December. We can also see that most purchases are made by customers who live in San Francisco, CA. The leading product in sales is AAA Batteries (followed closely by AA Batteries), and the product that generates the most revenue is the Macbook Pro.

This was a practice activity for myself on R Programming and creating reports with R Markdown. In it I showcased my ability to use %>%, ggplot2, arithmetic operators and group_by. I also utilized basic SQL and Excel functions.

SQL Queries for creating views:

``{sql `}

– Grouping by date and product for ease of use in ggplot2

SELECT DISTINCT(Product) AS Product, SUM(Price_Each) AS Revenue_Total, SUM(Quantity_Ordered) AS Quantity_Sold, Date FROM austin-oberg-portfolio.SalesData.tech_sales_2019 GROUP BY Date, Product ORDER BY Date;

– Looking at total unit sales by product

SELECT Product, SUM(Quantity_Ordered) AS Quantity_Ordered FROM austin-oberg-portfolio.SalesData.tech_sales_2019 GROUP BY Product ORDER BY Quantity_Ordered;

– Looking at total revenue by product

SELECT Product, SUM(Price_Each) AS Total_Revenue FROM austin-oberg-portfolio.SalesData.tech_sales_2019 GROUP BY Product ORDER BY Total_Revenue;

– Joining customer city data to tech_sales_2019 and dropping – Purchase_Address

SELECT DISTINCT(sales.Order_ID), sales.Product, sales.Quantity_Ordered, sales.Price_Each, sales.Date, cities.order_city FROM austin-oberg-portfolio.SalesData.sales_with_cities cities JOIN austin-oberg-portfolio.SalesData.tech_sales_2019sales ON cities.Order_ID = sales.Order_ID Order BY Date; ``{sql `}
